'''Sherry Farrell Racette''' is a [[Métis people (Canada)|Métis]] Canadian feminist scholar, author, and artist. She is best known for her contributions to [[Visual arts by indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indigenous art]] histories and [[Canadian art]] history<ref>{{Cite web|title = University of Manitoba - Faculty of Arts - Native Studies - Sherry Farrell Racette|url = http://umanitoba.ca/faculties/arts/departments/native_studies/people/3077.html|website = umanitoba.ca|accessdate = 2015-10-26}}</ref> and is an associate professor of Native Studies and Women's and Gender Studies at the [[University of Manitoba]].
==Life== Racette was born in Manitoba, and is of Métis ancestry. She is of a member of the [[Timiskaming First Nation]] and taught at [[Concordia University]] in 2007. She holds an master's degree in Education, from the [[University of Regina]], and completed her PhD in Native Studies, Anthropology, and History at the [[University of Manitoba]].
== Academic career == Racette is a board member of the Aboriginal Curatorial Collective,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sherry Farrell Racette|url = http://www.acc-cca.com/wordpress/curator-profile/sherry-farell-racette/|website = Aboriginal Curatorial Collective / Collectif des commissaires autochtones|accessdate = 2015-10-27|language = en}}</ref> and her artwork promotes Aboriginal and Aboriginal women's histories. Racette's paintings have been featured in a number of publications, and her work "''The Flower Beadwork People''" was published by the [[Gabriel Dumont Institute]] in 1992.<ref name=virtual>{{Cite web|title = The Virtual Museum of Métis History and Culture|url = http://www.metismuseum.ca/resource.php/06625|website = www.metismuseum.ca|accessdate = 2015-10-30}}</ref> Other artworks on display at the institute, created by Racette, include "''Keep Your Spirit Free''," (poster) and the collection of "''Flags of the Métis''"<ref name=virtual/> Racette's artwork is also exhibited at the Mackenzie Art Gallery in Saskatchewan.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Encyclopedia of Saskatchewan {{!}} Details|url = http://esask.uregina.ca/entry/farrell_racette_sherry.html|website = esask.uregina.ca|accessdate = 2015-10-30}}</ref> She is a member of the Saskatchewan Arts Board,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Saskatchewan Arts Board|url = http://www.artsboard.sk.ca/component/content/article/408-about-us/default20/1629-sherry-farrell-racette|website = www.artsboard.sk.ca|accessdate = 2015-10-30}}</ref> and also serves on the board of the Saskatchewan Heritage Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Saskatchewan NAC Artists {{!}} Sherry Farrell Racette|url = http://www.sknac.ca/index.php?page=ArtistDetail&id=31|website = www.sknac.ca|accessdate = 2015-10-30}}</ref> In 2009-2010, as a Resident Scholar at the School for Advanced Research, Racette created an exhibition on Material Culture as Encoded Objects and Memory.<ref>{{Cite web|title = SAR—Sherry Farrell Racette, Resident Scholar|url = http://sarweb.org/?resident_scholar_sherry_farrell_racette|website = sarweb.org|accessdate = 2015-10-30}}</ref> In 2013, she was an exhibition consultant for the Montreal McCord Museum's "''Wearing Our Identity : The First People's Collection''." Racette has been mentioned as an artist in the book titled " ''The Artist Herself : Self-Portraits by Canadian Historical Women Artist''s."
==Writing== Racette has illustrated several books, including ''The Flower Beadwork People'' (1985), ''Stories of the Road Allowance People'' (1995), ''Flies to the Moon'' (1999), and ''Little Voice'' (2001). She co-edited ''Clearing a Path: New Ways of Seeing Traditional Indigenous Art (2015)''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.goodminds.com/clearing-path-new-ways-seeing-traditional-indigenous-art-hardcover-ed|title=Clearing a Path: New Ways of Seeing Traditional Indigenous Art, hardcover ed {{!}} GoodMinds.com|website=www.goodminds.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-09}}</ref> with [[Carmen Robertson|Dr. Carmen Robertson]]. She has also published articles and essays in scholarly publications. Her scholarly background is in art history, education, history, anthropology and Native studies.
==Artwork== Racette creates paintings and multimedia works.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sherry Farrell Racette, PhD {{!}} IAIA|url = http://www.iaia.edu/museum/vision-project/authors/sherry-farrell-racette-phd/|website = www.iaia.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-30}}</ref> Her art has been featured in solo, group, and museum exhibitions, and she has won awards for her illustrated children's books. In 2012, she worked with project creator and lead coordinator, [[Christi Belcourt]], to co-curate "[[Walking with Our Sisters|Walking With Our sisters]]", a commemorative art installation that honours the lives of the hundreds of missing or murdered Indigenous women in Canada. The installation has toured since 2013, with exhibitions in Edmonton,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://walkingwithoursisters.ca/events/2013-2/edmonton/|title=Edmonton, AB - Telus Atrium|work=Walking With Our Sisters|access-date=2017-03-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Regina,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/989788/exhibit-honours-missing-and-murdered-indigenous-women/|title=Exhibit honours missing and murdered indigenous women|last=Smith|first=Kim|work=Global News|access-date=2017-03-09|language=en}}</ref> Parry Sound, Winnipeg, Sault St. Marie, Flin Flon, Thunder Bay,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/thunder-bay/walking-with-our-sisters-heads-to-thunder-bay-city-council-1.2987363|title=Walking with our Sisters seeks help preventing violence|work=CBC News|access-date=2017-03-09|language=en}}</ref> Saskatoon, Yellowknife, Whitehorse, Comox, Ottawa,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://carleton.ca/fass/2015/fass-blog-walking-with-our-sisters-and-other-journeys-by-sandra-dyck-director-of-the-carleton-university-art-gallery/|title=FASS Blog – Walking With Our Sisters and Other Journeys by Sandra Dyck (Director of the Carleton University Art Gallery) - Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences|work=Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences|access-date=2017-03-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Akwesasne, North Battleford, and Brandon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brandonu.ca/news/2016/01/22/brandon-university-to-host-walking-with-our-sisters-exhibit/|title=Brandon University to host Walking With Our Sisters exhibit|last=University|first=Brandon|work=Brandon University|access-date=2017-03-09|language=en-US}}</ref> In this exhibition, hundreds of artists donated hand-made moccasins to honour the lives of Aboriginal women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/art-exhibit-uses-moccasins-to-honour-missing-murdered-aboriginal-women-1.1741137|title=Art exhibit uses moccasins to honour missing, murdered aboriginal women|website=CTVNews|accessdate=2015-10-30}}</ref>
